<br>
1. It is believed Jesus was not born in December. The bible references sheperds watching there flocks, but during December in that geographical area flocks are brought in from pasture. <br>
<br>
2. Easter was adopted from a pagan fertility right. Hence the use of rabbits and eggs and flowers. It was changed to the Celebration of the Resurection to refocus the pagan's bachanallians that were celebrations of life and fertility. <br>
<br>
3. Christianities biggest boost came from a political stroke. At the time Rome was trying to bring its empire closer together, and many religious disputes errupted between the various religious factions. The emperor said Rome would have but one religion. It became Christianity.<br>
<br>
4. The day of worship was changed to Sunday to appease the Sun worshippers. God is light and all. The sabbath was originally on a Saturday.<br>
<br>
5. The modern image of the devil, comes from pan. The Christians assumed he was the devil when described by his worshippers as it did not fit in with any of there versions of divinity. In the Bible when satan is anthropomorhalized it is usually as a serpent or dragon.<br>
<br>
6. King Arthur, if he existed, had nothing to do with the Holy Grail. Arthur was a hero amongst the pagans of the British Isles. Hence, the references to such things as wizardry and Avalon. Both concepts which do not jive with common accepted Christian doctrine. <br>
<br>
7. Even before Jesus arrived on the scene the jews were doing such things. For instance, ancient Israelites turned Babylonian and Philistine gods such as Bel and Dagon into demons in their own cosmology. <br>
<br>
<br>
Also in reference to wicca, <br>
There is a modern trend in current neopagan circles to reinterpret historical witchcraft into some sweet bloodless religion about female empowerment. In truth the anciet Greeks and Romans were terrified of the witches of Thessaly. <br>
-Neil Gaiman <br>
Upon research I discovered the witches of Thessaly derived their &quot;powers&quot; through the gnawing of the flesh of the dead. Human sacrifice was also attributed to them. It is not unheard of for people to offer animals or in some stories children to the witches to sacrifice to recieve the benefit of their magicks.<br>
<br>
This is just some lost bits on the pasts of religions that i thought may interest some. It was not meant to offend some, but as with anything which may go against an accepted belief it may. <br>
